---
import { Image } from "astro:assets";
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";
import "../styles/englishlive.css";
const title = "EF English Live - Alexis Morin";
const metaD =
  "EF English Live, a UX design project by Alexis Morin. Adapting a legacy web-based English learning platform for modern mobile experiences on iOS and Android.";

import googlePlay from "../images/googlePlay.svg";
import appStore from "../images/appStore.svg";
import forSinceWeb from "../images/projects/englishlive/for-since-web@2x.png";
import forSinceAndroid from "../images/projects/englishlive/for-since-mobile-android@2x.png";
import forSinceIos from "../images/projects/englishlive/for-since-mobile-ios@2x.png";
import structure1 from "../images/projects/englishlive/structure-1.jpg";
import structure2 from "../images/projects/englishlive/structure-2.jpg";
import structure3 from "../images/projects/englishlive/structure-3.jpg";
import structure4 from "../images/projects/englishlive/structure-4.jpg";
import structure5 from "../images/projects/englishlive/structure-5.jpg";
---

<Base title={title} metaD={metaD}>
  <div class="body-img bdimg-classroom"></div>

  <div id="intro"><h2 class="visually-hidden">EF English Live</h2></div>

  <div class="content" id="englishliveintro">
    <section>
      <h2>An app 20 years in the making</h2>
      <p>
        Founded in 1996, EF teaches English to 1 000 000 paying subscribers
        studying and hires over 2 000 teachers.
      </p>
    </section>
  </div>

  <div class="content contribution">
    <section>
      <p>
        My contribution to the project was to:
        <ul>
          <li>Adapt desktop interactions of English lessons for mobile,</li>
          <li>Build mobile interactive prototypes of lesson ideas,</li>
          <li>Design activity templates unique to mobile,</li>
          <li>Create UX designs to be used in 17 languages,</li>
        </ul>
      </p>
      <p>
        <span class="am-bold">Compay:</span> EF Education First (Shanghai, China)<br
        />
        <span class="am-bold">Team:</span> User Experience &amp; Design<br />
        <span class="am-bold">Role:</span> UX Designer, Prototyper<br />
        <span class="am-bold">Timeline:</span> April - October 2014<br />
        <span class="am-bold">Status:</span> EF English Live is available on Google
        Play and the Apple App Store.
      </p>
      <p>
        <a
          href="https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=com.ef.core.engage.englishtown"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noreferrer"
          style="display: inline-block;"
        >
          <Image
            src={googlePlay}
            height={50}
            alt="English Live on Google Play"
            style="display: inline;"
          />
        </a>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<a
          href="https://itunes.apple.com/ca/app/ef-english-live-for-iphone/id961304373?mt=8"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noreferrer"
          style="display: inline-block;"
        >
          <Image
            src={appStore}
            height={50}
            alt="English Live on the App Store"
            style="display: inline;"
          />
        </a>
      </p>
    </section>
  </div>
  <div class="content">
    <section>
      <h3>The challenge</h3>
      <p>
        To expand a successful (but legacy) English learning web product to
        mobile, across platforms, while maintaining educational value.
      </p>
      <h3>From this</h3>
      <Image
        src={forSinceWeb}
        alt="A dated-looking website explains English verb tenses"
      />
      <h3>To this</h3>
      <div class="multi-col" style="--gtc: 1fr 1fr;">
        <Image
          src={forSinceAndroid}
          alt="A modern iOS app explains English verb tenses"
        />
        <Image
          src={forSinceIos}
          alt="A modern Android app explains English verb tenses"
        />
      </div>
    </section>
  </div>

  <div class="content">
    <section>
      <h3>Structure</h3>
      <p>
        To better suit a mobile form factor and the context of our students, our
        team devised ways to break down existing web content into smaller,
        bite-sized morcels of learning. Here is an overview of the learning flow
        of the app, organised in these shorter bursts of learning.
      </p>
      <Image
        src={structure1}
        alt="app screens for Login, Course Overview, Lesson Overview"
      />
      <Image
        src={structure2}
        alt="app screens for Module Introduction, Video Vocabulary"
      />
      <Image
        src={structure3}
        alt="app screens for Video Vocabulary, Vocuabulary review"
      />
      <Image
        src={structure4}
        alt="app screens for Reading activity, Audio multiple choice"
      />
      <Image
        src={structure5}
        alt="app screens for Multiple choice, Step complete, Lesson complete"
      />
    </section>
  </div>

  <div class="content contribution">
    <section>
      <p>
        The goal of this project was to leverage the existing English Live
        platform on desktop Web and rethink the design and interaction patterns
        of the e-learning templates in a way better suited to mobile platforms.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>My involvement</strong> was to rethink these interactions and create
        wireframes and interactive prototypes for more than 10 activity templates.
        Expanding beyond the original scope of the project, I also designed some activity
        templates unique to mobile.
      </p>
      <p>
        Framing this work, our team also took into consideration our target
        customers, the existing language barrier, mobile OS design consistency
        and even 17 supported UI languages. The work covered in English Live for
        iOS &amp; Android: ideation, sketching, wireframes, user testing &amp;
        research, visual style exploration, interactive prototyping.
      </p>
    </section>
  </div>
</Base>
